<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="67" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="66" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Revue francaise d'Entomologie" pageId="6" pageNumber="71" pagination="77 - 92" title="New genera and species of Eumolpinae from New Caledonia (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae)." volume="29" year="2007">Jolivet et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes bertiae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertiae">Stethotes bertiae</taxonomicName>
based on three specimens collected at Col 
<normalizedToken originalValue="d’Amieu">d'Amieu</normalizedToken>
and compared the new species with 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. minuta" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="minuta">S. minuta</taxonomicName>
Jacoby, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. similis" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="similis">S. similis</taxonomicName>
Gressitt and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. mimica" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="mimica">S. mimica</taxonomicName>
Gressitt, all endemic from New Guinea (
<bibRefCitation author="Gressitt, JL" journalOrPublisher="Pacific Insects" pageId="6" pageNumber="71" pagination="777 - 800" title="Chrysomelid beetles from the Papuan subregion, 3 (Eumolpinae, 1)." volume="8" year="1966">Gressitt 1966</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Revue francaise d'Entomologie" pageId="6" pageNumber="71" pagination="77 - 92" title="New genera and species of Eumolpinae from New Caledonia (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae)." volume="29" year="2007">Jolivet et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
). The genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Stethotes</taxonomicName>
was proposed with descriptions of nine species from Java, New Guinea, Borneo, and the Moluccas (
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Baly 1865-1867</bibRefCitation>
) and later shown to be particularly species-rich in New Guinea (
<bibRefCitation author="Gressitt, JL" journalOrPublisher="Pacific Insects" pageId="6" pageNumber="71" pagination="777 - 800" title="Chrysomelid beetles from the Papuan subregion, 3 (Eumolpinae, 1)." volume="8" year="1966">Gressitt 1966</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Medvedev, LN" journalOrPublisher="Stuttgarter Beitraege zur Naturkunde" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="371 - 408" title="New genera and species of Zeugophorinae and Eumolpinae (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae) from New Guinea." volume="2" year="2009">Medvedev 2009</bibRefCitation>
), but also 
<pageBreakToken pageId="1" pageNumber="66" start="start">recorded</pageBreakToken>
from other areas in the Australasian region, including Fiji and Samoa (
<bibRefCitation pageId="1" pageNumber="66">Maulik 1929</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bryant, GE" journalOrPublisher="Pacific Science" pageId="6" pageNumber="71" pagination="3 - 91" title="Chrysomelidae of Fiji (Coleoptera)." volume="11" year="1957">Bryant and Gressitt 1957</bibRefCitation>
). In this geographic context, it seemed reasonable to find the genus in New Caledonia as well. But the finding of 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes bertiae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertiae">Stethotes bertiae</taxonomicName>
had implications beyond the discovery of a genus that had not been previously recorded from New Caledonia and is not known from Australia either. 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Stethotes</taxonomicName>
belongs to the tribe 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="tribe" tribe="Typophorini">Typophorini</taxonomicName>
, a lineage most diverse in the Old World, particularly in South East Asia and in the Western Pacific, and this lineage is also the one thriving in Fiji, with important biogeographic connections with New Caledonia (
<bibRefCitation author="Keppel, G" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Biogeography" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="1035 - 1054" title="Changing perspectives on the biogeography of the tropical South Pacific: influences of dispersal, vicariance and extinction." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-2699.2009.02095.x" volume="36" year="2009">Keppel et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
). Interestingly, the vast majority of 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="subfamily" subfamily="Eumolpinae">Eumolpinae</taxonomicName>
in New Caledonia belong to the tribe 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="tribe" tribe="Eumolpini">Eumolpini</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gomez-Zurita, J" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="6" pageNumber="71" pagination="33 - 44" title="Rhyparidafoaensis (Jolivet, Verma &amp; Mille) nov. comb. (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae) and implications for the colonization of New Caledonia." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.157.1320" volume="157" year="2011 a">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gómez-Zurita">Gomez-Zurita</normalizedToken>
2011a
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Papadopoulou, A" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="473 - 495" title="Diversity and diversification of Eumolpinae (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae) in New Caledonia." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/zoj.12039" volume="168" year="2013">Papadopoulou et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
: note that in these works, the names 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="tribe" tribe="Colaspoidini">Colaspoidini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="tribe" tribe="Nodinini">Nodinini</taxonomicName>
were used instead of 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="tribe" tribe="Eumolpini">Eumolpini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="tribe" tribe="Typophorini">Typophorini</taxonomicName>
, respectively). To our knowledge, the only exceptions were 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1861" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Rhyparida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhyparida foaensis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foaensis">Rhyparida foaensis</taxonomicName>
(Jolivet, Verma &amp; Mille, 2007) and three species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Stethotes</taxonomicName>
, incluiding 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. bertiae" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="species" species="bertiae">S. bertiae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gomez-Zurita, J" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="6" pageNumber="71" pagination="33 - 44" title="Rhyparidafoaensis (Jolivet, Verma &amp; Mille) nov. comb. (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae) and implications for the colonization of New Caledonia." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.157.1320" volume="157" year="2011 a">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gómez-Zurita">Gomez-Zurita</normalizedToken>
2011a
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="66">
The original description of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. bertiae" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="species" species="bertiae">S. bertiae</taxonomicName>
was very generic, without much useful information on characters that could help in recognizing the correct generic placement of the species, except perhaps the two differentiated arrangements of elytral punctation: confused at basal half and aligned at apical half of elytra. However, the original description included a photograph of the holotype (
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Revue francaise d'Entomologie" pageId="6" pageNumber="71" pagination="77 - 92" title="New genera and species of Eumolpinae from New Caledonia (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae)." volume="29" year="2007">Jolivet et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
: 91). 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes bertiae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertiae">Stethotes bertiae</taxonomicName>
has the size, the characteristic fusiform shape, the long antennae, the strong punctation (aligned at apical half of elytra), and most critically, entire tibiae of 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Acronymolpus</taxonomicName>
, a character clearly showing that the species should not be placed in the 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="tribe" tribe="Typophorini">Typophorini</taxonomicName>
. Moreover, the revision of 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Acronymolpus</taxonomicName>
included one species, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. meteorus" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="species" species="meteorus">A. meteorus</taxonomicName>
Samuelson, also collected in the Col 
<normalizedToken originalValue="d’Amieu">d'Amieu</normalizedToken>
and the nearby Plateau de Dogny and sharing all the (apomorphic) peculiarities of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. bertiae" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="species" species="bertiae">S. bertiae</taxonomicName>
. Among these, it is worth mentioning the heavy punctation of pronotum and basal half of elytra, the reddish testaceous coloration of abdominal ventrites, and the finely wrinkled hypomera, referred to as &quot;with heavy isodiametric sculpture&quot; by 
<bibRefCitation author="Samuelson, GA" editor="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="93 - 102" title="Acronymolpus, a new genus of Eumolpinae, endemic to New Caledonia (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.547.9698" volume="547" volumeTitle="Research on Chrysomelidae 5." year="2015">Samuelson (2015)</bibRefCitation>
. There is no doubt that Samuelson's species is the same that had been described years earlier by 
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Revue francaise d'Entomologie" pageId="6" pageNumber="71" pagination="77 - 92" title="New genera and species of Eumolpinae from New Caledonia (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae)." volume="29" year="2007">Jolivet et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
, and this claim was recently confirmed by G. Allan Samuelson himself, upon our exchange of opinions, by comparing the type of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. bertiae" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="species" species="bertiae">S. bertiae</taxonomicName>
with his own specimens (G. Allan Samuelson, pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="67" pageId="1" pageNumber="66">
The original work describing 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes bertiae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertiae">Stethotes bertiae</taxonomicName>
included a drawing of the penis, but as it is customary in contributions by the authors of this species, the sexual organ was shown in lateral view, which is of very limited utility for identification purposes (
<bibRefCitation author="Gomez-Zurita, J" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="6" pageNumber="71" pagination="31 - 46" title="Revision of New Caledonian species of Eumolpinae described by K. M. Heller (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae)." volume="3060" year="2011 b">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gómez-Zurita">Gomez-Zurita</normalizedToken>
2011b
</bibRefCitation>
). In turn, the description of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. meteorus" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="species" species="meteorus">A. meteorus</taxonomicName>
lacked any reference to genital structures. The dissection of the new material available for this species showed that they are all males, and male genitalia could be prepared and described focusing on taxonomically relevant characters for the first time (Fig. 1a, c): the penis is narrow and slender, narrower in median part and curved in lateral view, with apex tapering and more strongly bent ventrally, as described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Revue francaise d'Entomologie" pageId="6" pageNumber="71" pagination="77 - 92" title="New genera and species of Eumolpinae from New Caledonia (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae)." volume="29" year="2007">Jolivet et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
; distal end is flattened dorsoventrally, with sides straight and converging to blunt apex with a short median notch. The dissection of the specimens of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. turbo" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="species" species="turbo">A. turbo</taxonomicName>
, sympatric and syntopic (judging from collection data shown in labels) with 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. meteorus" pageId="1" pageNumber="66" rank="species" species="meteorus">A. meteorus</taxonomicName>
in every one of the sites where 
<pageBreakToken pageId="2" pageNumber="67" start="start">this</pageBreakToken>
species has been found, showed that they were all females and, as mentioned above, are interpreted here as conspecific with 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. bertiae" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" rank="species" species="bertiae">A. bertiae</taxonomicName>
. The spermatheca of the species is described here for the first time (Fig. 1e): spermatheca slender, with nodulus and cornu feebly curved and more or less at right or slightly obtuse angle; cornu thicker than nodulus and blunt at apex; nodulus with bulging insertion of spermathecal gland at middle; spermathecal duct inserted nearly at base of nodulus and bent abruptly.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="2" pageNumber="67">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="67">
Figure 1. Ventral and lateral views of the penises of a 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus bertiae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertiae">Acronymolpus bertiae</taxonomicName>
(Jolivet, Verma &amp; Mille) and b 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. jourdani" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" rank="species" species="jourdani">A. jourdani</taxonomicName>
(Jolivet, Verma &amp; Mille). Dorsal view of the distal ends of the penis of c 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. bertiae" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" rank="species" species="bertiae">A. bertiae</taxonomicName>
and d 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. jourdani" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" rank="species" species="jourdani">A. jourdani</taxonomicName>
. Spermathecae of e 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. bertiae" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" rank="species" species="bertiae">A. bertiae</taxonomicName>
and f 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. jourdani" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" rank="species" species="jourdani">A. jourdani</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="67">
Based on this complete account, which takes into account geographical but mainly anatomical data and the recognition of sexual dimorphism in the species as described above, three taxonomic acts are necessary. The first is the transfer of 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes bertiae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertiae">Stethotes bertiae</taxonomicName>
to the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Acronymolpus</taxonomicName>
, resulting in 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus bertiae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertiae">Acronymolpus bertiae</taxonomicName>
(Jolivet, Verma &amp; Mille, 2007), comb. n., and the other two are recognizing that 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. meteorus" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" rank="species" species="meteorus">A. meteorus</taxonomicName>
(males) and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. turbo" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" rank="species" species="turbo">A. turbo</taxonomicName>
(females) are junior synonyms of this taxon; thus, 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes bertiae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertiae">Stethotes bertiae</taxonomicName>
Jolivet, Verma &amp; Mille, 2007 = 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus meteorus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meteorus">Acronymolpus meteorus</taxonomicName>
Samuelson, 2015, syn. n. and 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus turbo" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turbo">Acronymolpus turbo</taxonomicName>
Samuelson, 2015, syn. n.
</paragraph>
